<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-06-14T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-06-14T02:00:00-05:00" n="584" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d584">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">893.20/805: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-14T14:00:00+07:00">June 14,
                                1944—2 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received June 1410:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1028. Drumright reports from Sian in telegram June 10 he is informed that,
                        evidently in connection with general withdrawal of Russian military
                        advisers, those to 8th War Area, Sian, were departing that day for Russia.
                        In despatch June 7 Penfield in Chengtu states 6 Soviet military aviation
                        advisers left there June 6 en route to Russia on expiration of
                        contracts.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>